The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and have a busy program.
He will first go to the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the Committee who chose him in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The planning of the presidential couple then provides for an interview with the king of Norway Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will meet his sumum in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious reward.
He will be the fourth American President to receive it, but only the third who will be awarded the prize in the Committee's very presence.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan at the award ceremony.
The President does not want to avoid this because he is aware that he receives this prize by being a president who is waging a war in two countries at present.
He reinforced the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics will forget to highlight.
During the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a cheque of ten million Swedish kroners (about 1.1 million Euros).
He intends to donate to charitable works, but has not yet concretely decided which ones.
His program will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of the government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant at this price at first.
He mentioned, for example, feeling that he did not fully deserve it.
He also repeated several times that it was not a price for himself, but for all who defend the same values as him.
From the announcement, he stated that it would be an invitation to act for him.
