Czech discovery: a substance that works on HIV-endurant viruses as well
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new combinations that can slow the proliferation of HIV in the organism.
The main benefit of the improved substance is that it also acts on viruses that have already developed immunity to drugs.
In some cases, the fact that the combination does not deal as intensively with the current variants of the virus as well as with some already available drugs is the case.
It is not possible to cure AIDS at the present time.
However, the life of the sick can be radically extended through a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of HIV in the body.
Their consumption, however, results in a series of side effects.
In addition, the repression of this multiplication has the effect of developing what is called resistant viruses on which drugs have no effect anymore.
The work of the experts from three institutions, the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the VŠCHT of Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to confront the resistance of the virus.
They showed that substances called metalocarborans act on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are a combination of bore, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
This combination blocks the development of the virus in a different way from all the drugs used so far and that is why they could overcome the problem of resistance.
The work of researchers leads them to discover new, improved substances based on their knowledge of the molecular mechanics of their bindings on virus proteins.
Metalocarbons have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiple-walled cages are formed by the atoms of bore, hydrogen and carbon and connected by a metal atom, in this case the cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus.
HIV protein is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential to the life cycle of the virus.
