75% of working mothers have had professional problems because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is reflected in the study \"Fecundity and professional career of women in Spain\", carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey, carried out on 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no room for doubt: 75% of working mothers have seen their careers limited because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences regarding the beginning of life in marriage and the number of children, whether or not the woman works and the type of employment employed.
Those who do not have activity outside the home, work part-time or work unsteady, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with a stable job, mainly in the public sector, refuse to enter into married life and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of fixed employment have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after having been married. This figure goes to 4.1 in those working in the public sector. \"These data show that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to obtain it, which led them to put away the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exercised greatly influences maternity, but less the starting date of the common life\", explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that increases the difference between the marriage age of women and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and their first child is late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the group between 35 and 49 years of age, those who did elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years on average.
\"Another differentiation also appears among women, depending on their level of study.
While those who have completed basic studies marry and have their first child before finding stable employment, those who have done middle or higher education reverse this program and give priority to achieving stable work as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child,\" said Delgado.
