Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As was the case with the ABS brake anti-locking system and as will be done with the ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will be a mandatory component on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of deficiency has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure, imposed by the European Union, is to strengthen pedestrian protection, even though, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many rear shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency detected by the system thanks to the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure to the end.
According to a study conducted by the manufacturer of Bosch car components, one third of the drivers involved in an accident were unable to rely on the brake before the collision, and half of them had not benefited from all of their strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, in revenge, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularization of so-called intelligent emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one-on-four disaster with wounded would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, by means of a radar or a camera, detects the obstacles and prevents the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps him by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and although the collision is inevitable, the device exerts the maximum effort on the brakes to minimize the damage.
